    "rawCode": "F1010",
    "shortDesc": "Alcohol abuse, uncomplicated",
    "longDesc": "Alcohol abuse, uncomplicated",
    "plainEnglish": "Alcohol abuse means someone is drinking alcohol in a harmful way that's causing problems in their life—such as trouble at work, school, relationships, or health—but they're not yet physically dependent on it. Unlike addiction, the person hasn't developed a physical dependence where they experience withdrawal symptoms when they stop drinking, but their drinking pattern is still dangerous and unsustainable. This diagnosis captures ongoing problematic drinking habits that need medical attention before they worsen.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, psychiatrists, addiction medicine specialists, and substance abuse counselors commonly use this code when evaluating patients with drinking problems. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients seeking counseling, behavioral therapy, or medical evaluation for alcohol-related issues, and may be associated with referrals to rehabilitation programs or support services.",
