    "shortDesc": "Schizophrenia, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Schizophrenia, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Schizophrenia is a serious mental health condition where a person experiences significant breaks with reality, including hallucinations (hearing or seeing things others don't), delusions (false beliefs), confused thinking, and difficulty with emotional expression or motivation. This diagnosis indicates schizophrenia has been diagnosed, but the specific type or pattern hasn't been clearly identified or documented yet.",
    "whoUses": "Psychiatrists, psychiatric nurse practitioners, and mental health clinicians use this code when diagnosing and treating schizophrenia, particularly during initial evaluations or when the presentation doesn't fit a more specific subtype. This code commonly appears on patient EOB statements and mental health referrals, and is essential for insurance coverage of antipsychotic medications and psychiatric hospitalization or outpatient services.",
